. It is also the spelling preferred in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, which has had some influence on its selection as a given name. There has been a sharp rise in its popularity since the turn of the century. <i>Lucas</i> is now also used as an Anglicized form of various Eastern European equivalents (  see the cognates listed at  Luke  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Luke","meanings":["Middle English vernacular form of   Lucas  , Latin form of the post-classical Greek name <i>Loukas</i> ‘man from Lucania’. This owes its perennial popularity throughout Christian Europe to the fact that, from the 2nd century onwards, the third gospel in the New Testament has been ascribed to the Lucas or Luke mentioned at various places in Acts and in the Epistles. Little is known about him beyond the facts that he was a doctor, a Gentile, and a friend and convert of St Paul. The name was borne by the character  Luke Skywalker  in the film Star Wars (  1977 ), and rose sharply in popularity in the 1990s."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354912,"age":59,"year":"1241","julianDay":2174327,"description":"The Mongolian Tatars devastated the country. Their presence, which lasted a year, halted development for at least a century. After the warfare with the Hungarians, the Tatars did not continue towards the west.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lucas I Hirscher was born in 1182, in Braşov, Transylvania, Hungary, his father, Janos I. VON HIRSCHER KRONSTADT, was 23 and his mother, Sofia Von Querfurt Magdeburg, was 22. He married UNK- B Hirscher in 1212, in Braşov, Transylvania, Hungary. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 7 daughters. He died in 1250, in his hometown, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1182–1250":"1182–1250","1187–Female":"1187–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1213–Male":"1213–Surnud","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1216–Female":"1216–Surnud","1219–1256":"1219–1256","1221–Female":"1221–Surnud","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1226–Female":"1226–Surnud","–Male